We have $$f(f(x)-y) = (f(x)-y)(f(y) + 1).$$
Therefore, for each $\alpha \in \mathbb{R},$ there is a unique $x =f(y)+ 1$ such that $f(x)-y = \alpha.$
That is,
\begin{align*}
&\text{If $\alpha < 0,$ we have a unique solution $x, y$ such that $f(x) - y = \alpha.$}
\end{align*}
